 ### Proof
 We have that \[\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\ 7 & -1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & -5 \\ 0 & 4 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (2)(1) + (3)(0) & (2)(-5) + (3)(4) \\ (7)(1) + (-1)(0) & (7)(-5) + (-1)(4) \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 2 \\ 7 & -39 \end{pmatrix}}.\]
 *)

theorem
fixes A B C :: "int^2^2"
assumes h0 : "A = ( | 2, 3 |, | 7, -1 | )"
and h1 : "B = ( | 1, -5 |, | 0, 4 | )"
and h2 : "C = ( | 2, 2 |, | 7, -39 | )"
shows  "A *v B = C"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Given two 2x2 matrices A and B, with A being the matrix with first row [2, 3] and second row [7, -1] and B being the matrix with first row [1, -5] and second row [0, 4], find the matrix product of A and B.
